  "prompt": "Is it a felony to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a felony in most jurisdictions, including the United States. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally obtained money (from activities such as drug trafficking, fraud, or other criminal enterprises) appear legitimate by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. Criminal activities associated with money laundering include:\n\n1. **Placement**: Introducing the illegal funds into the financial system.\n2. **Layering**: Conducting a series of transactions to obscure the origin of the funds.\n3. **Integration**: Making the funds appear legitimate by integrating them into the economy.\n\nIn the United States, money laundering is prosecuted under federal law, primarily through the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986**. Penalties for money laundering can include:\n\n- Significant fines (up to $500,000 or twice the value of the funds involved, whichever is greater).\n- Imprisonment for up to 20 years or more, depending on the severity and scale of the offense.\n- Forfeiture of assets involved in the laundering scheme.\n\nAdditionally, many other countries have stringent laws and penalties for money laundering, often aligned with international standards set by organizations like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**.",
